e of manpower in the Canadian Expeditionary Force, Filling the Ranks examines the administrative and organizational changes that fostered efficiency and sustained the army. Richard Holt describes national civilian and military recruitment policies and criteria both inside and outside of Canada; efforts to recruit women, convicts, and members of First Nations, African Canadian, Asian, and Slavic communities; the conduct of entry-level training; and the development of a coherent reinforcement structure. Canada’s ability to fill the ranks with trained soldiers ultimately helped make the Corps an elite formation within the British Expeditionary Force. Based on extensive research in British and Canadian archives, Filling the Ranks provides a wealth of new information on Canada"s role in the Great War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArmed ForcesxPersonnel management. 0aGuerre mondiale, 1914-1918xHistoire des unitésxCanada. 0aGuerre mondiale, 1914-1918. 0aRecruiting and enlistment. 0aRegimental historiesxCanada. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xRegimental historiesxCanada. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xRegimental historieszCanada. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh1 aCook, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGranatstein, J.L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077354910440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773549104423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773549104/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP